  <img class="rightFloat" src="../media/gt_set3.1_06.jpg" mode="1" id="1001"/>
  
  	<ol id="questionList">
	
	<li>Which of the following people would you write a formalletter to?
	<list class="answerList">
	<li><a id="t1">a close friend</a></li>
	<li><a id="t2">someone you have never met</a></li>
	<li><a id="t3">someone you do not know very well</a></li>
	<li><a id="t4">a close relative</a></li>
	<li><a id="t5">the editor of a newspaper</a></li>
	<li><a id="t6">a prospective employer</a></li>
	</list></li>
	<p class="linespace"></p>
	
	<li>When we do not know the name of the person we arewriting to we begin the letter with 'Dear Sir/Madam'.Which ending is the most appropriate?
	<list class="answerList">
	<li><a id="t7">Yours faithfully</a></li>
	<li><a id="t8">Yours sincerely</a></li>
	<li><a id="t9">All the best</a></li>
	</list></li>
	<p class="linespace"></p>

	<li>When we know the recipient's surname, we use it in thesalutation, for example 'Dear Miss Barnes'. Which endingis the most appropriate?
	<list class="answerList">
	<li><a id="t10">Yours faithfully</a></li>
	<li><a id="t11">Yours sincerely</a></li>
	<li><a id="t12">All the best</a></li>
	</list></li>
	<p class="linespace"></p>
  
	<li>Which of the following openings are suitable for a formalletter?
	<list class="answerList">
	<li><a id="t13">I am writing to enquire about ...</a></li>
	<li><a id="t14">I am writing to inform you ...</a></li>
	<li><a id="t15">Just a quick note to ...</a></li>
	<li><a id="t16">This is just to let you know ...</a></li>
	<li><a id="t17">Thanks for your letter. It was great to hear ...</a></li>
	<li><a id="t18">Thank you for your letter of ...</a></li>
	<li><a id="t19">I am writing to apply for ...</a></li>
	<li><a id="t20">I saw your advertisement in ...</a></li>
	<li><a id="t21">Sorry I haven't been in touch for so long but ...</a></li>
	<li><a id="t22">I am writing to apologise for ...</a></li>
	</list></li>
	<p class="linespace"></p>
 
	<li>Which closing sentences are suitable for a formal letter?
	<list class="answerList">
	<li><a id="t23">I would appreciate a reply by return of post.</a></li>
	<li><a id="t24">Hope to hear from you very soon.</a></li>
	<li><a id="t25">I'm really looking forward to hearing all your news.</a></li>
	<li><a id="t26">Drop me a line when you can.</a></li>
	<li><a id="t27">I look forward to hearing from you in the near future.</a></li>
	<li><a id="t28">With thanks for your help in this matter.</a></li>
	<li><a id="t29">Thanks for everything.</a></li>
	<li><a id="t30">Thank you for your kind attention.</a></li>
	<li><a id="t31">Please feel free to contact me for further information.</a></li>
	<li><a id="t32">Take care and do keep in touch!</a></li>
	</list></li>
	<p class="linespace"></p>
  
	<li>Which of the following are found mainly in formal letters?
	<list class="answerList">
	<li><a id="t33">colloquial language</a></li>
	<li><a id="t34">full forms (e.g. I am, I would like, I have written)</a></li>
	<li><a id="t35">short forms (e.g. I'm, I'd like, I've written)</a></li>
	<li><a id="t36">impersonal style and tone</a></li>
	<li><a id="t37">personal style and tone</a></li>
	<li><a id="t38">phrasal verbs</a></li>
	<li><a id="t39">short, simple sentences</a></li>
	<li><a id="t40">indirect questions</a></li>
	<li><a id="t41">polite phrases</a></li>
	<li><a id="t42">idioms</a></li>
	</list></li>
